reviews.review_text:
They always played their best at RFK The 93 shows are no exception.  The sound of this recording is excellent, much better than one other that has 15 reviews.  I was at both RFK shows, so I know they both smoked.  Made up for the snowed-out 3/13 and mailed-in 3/14 show which was the only other show I caught that year.  First set standouts here include Half-Step and Althea.  Cassidy was nice and long, but Jerry didn't really bring it this time.  In the second set, things picked up with China>Rider.  I don't know about Bob turning over his usual guitar line to Vince, but once the jam got going it didn't matter.  Saint of Circumstance was not my first choice, but it shined here.  Uncle John's especially went over the top this night, a possible best-ever version.  The camera switched to Vince when playing his last of multiple runs in the lo-o-o-ong 7/4 jam at the end, and his jaw was dropping to his keyboard, such was the excitement of that moment.  We almost needed a breather after that, and they obliged with Corinna, not one of my favorites.  But the outro jam got out there a good bit before seguing into one of the best Drums I've heard.  It featured a good deal of talking drum and something that sounded like bongos.  Space showed off the versatility Jerry was able to get out of Rosebud with its built-in MIDI.

Only thing is, both nights, the after-space part is not so hot, like they got tired, but that's understandable -- they're both long shows, and it was hot in that stadium -- the weather, not just the playing.  Why else bag The Other One, which they teased, in favor of Miracle, which had no jam at all?  Although Jerry certainly sounded like he wanted to steer the band that way.  I can imagine the in-ear monitors conversation.  "Come on, Bob, let's play The Other One!"  "No, Jerry, it's Miracle."  "OK, FINE!!!" 
Wharf Rat didn't really generate much intensity either.  Bruce and Vince made some nice contributions, but I need wailing, take-charge guitar on this song, and Jerry didn't deliver.  Sugar Magnolia brought the energy back up to a rousing finish.

Sting opened both shows, and Jerry came out to play the last song with his band both times.  I'd like to find recordings of those songs!
